[[sn:Non-sect radical]]
[[ja:ノンセクト・ラジカル]]

{{No footnotes|date=2019-12-02}}
'''Nonsect Radical''' (ノンセクト・ラジカル) refers to activists and groups that are not affiliated with any faction established since the era of {{ill|All-Campus Joint Struggle Council|ja|全学共闘会議|lt=All-Campus Joint Struggle|lt_ja=全共闘|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/All-Campus Joint Struggle Council|qq=}}.

== Etymology ==
The term “Nonsect” means “not belonging to an existing {{ill|sect|ja|セクト|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/sect|qq=}} (faction) or {{ill|Nonpartisan|ja|無党派|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nonpartisan|qq=}},” while “Radical” (radical) signifies {{ill|radicalism|ja|急進主義|lt=Radical|lt_ja=急進的|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/radicalism|qq=}}. (Its original sense derives from the same root as {{ill|Radish|ja|ハツカダイコン|lt=Radish|lt_ja=ラディッシュ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Radish|qq=}}, meaning “fundamental” or “radical.”)

== Overview ==
The {{ill|Student Movement|ja|学生運動|lt=University Struggle|lt_ja=大学闘争|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Student Movement|qq=}} of the {{ill|1960s|ja|1960th year 代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1960s|qq=}} was led by the {{ill|New Left|ja|新左翼|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/New Left|qq=}} factions, but later expanded to include ordinary students. In the process, students and {{ill|citizens|ja|市民|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/citizens|qq=}} with a shared sense of purpose spontaneously organized themselves into groups that conducted university struggles. These groups did not operate as a faction; instead, they carried out their activities as part of the loosely connected {{ill|All-Campus Joint Struggle Council|ja|全学共闘会議|lt=All-Campus Joint Struggle|lt_ja=全共闘|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/All-Campus Joint Struggle Council|qq=}} movement. In addition to adherents of {{ill|Marxism|ja|マルクス主義|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Marxism|qq=}}, there were also proponents of {{ill|Anarchism|ja|アナキズム|lt=Anarchist|lt_ja=アナキスト|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Anarchism|qq=}} and advocates of a citizen {{ill|Revolution|ja|革命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Revolution|qq=}} within the {{ill|Commune|ja|コミューン|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Commune|qq=}} framework. They shared a common criticism of both the {{ill|Japanese Communist Party|ja|日本共産党|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Communist Party|qq=}} and the {{ill|Japanese Democratic Youth League|ja|日本民主青年同盟|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese Democratic Youth League|qq=}}, aligning them with other New Left factions.

Some have argued that Nonsect Radical itself evolved into a sort of pseudo-faction, and that the emergence of dominant leaders made internal criticism ({{ill|Criticism and self-criticism (Marxism–Leninism)|ja|自己批判|lt=Internal Criticism|lt_ja=内部批判|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Criticism and self-criticism (Marxism–Leninism)|qq=}}) difficult.

Essentially, it was a collective of those opposing established powers—not only the {{ill|State Power|ja|国家権力|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/State Power|qq=}} but also the entrenched authorities represented by groups such as the Japanese Communist Party and other New Left factions ({{ill|Power|ja|権力|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Power|qq=}}). The cross-organizational expansion of the All-Campus Joint Struggle was, in part, due to Nonsect participants joining the movement on a nonpartisan basis, thereby acting as a buffer between factions. However, lacking a clear ideology or a robust organization, and with some participants engaging in a more festive, transient manner, the foundation of the All-Campus Joint Struggle was never monolithic.

As the student movement waned and conflicts between factions intensified, some Nonsect activists were absorbed into existing groups or transformed into {{ill|Political Activist|ja|政治活動家|lt=Activist|lt_ja=活動家|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Political Activist|qq=}} roles, while many others gradually distanced themselves from the movement altogether.

== Current Situation ==
Although the Nonsect movement has been said to decline steadily since the All-Campus Joint Struggle era, its freedom from the constraints of established organizations allows it to respond rapidly and flexibly to contemporary issues. In recent years, groups have taken up the banner of {{ill|Constitutional Protection|ja|護憲|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Constitutional Protection|qq=}} to engage in anti-war and peace movements, have focused on issues such as {{ill|Postwar Compensation|ja|戦後補償|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Postwar Compensation|qq=}} and {{ill|Social Inequality|ja|格差社会|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Social Inequality|qq=}}, and have worked to expand their Ranks by allying with overseas {{ill|Anti-Globalization|ja|反グローバリゼーション|lt=Anti-Globalism|lt_ja=反グローバリズム|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Anti-Globalization|qq=}} organizations. Since the 2010 fiscal year, some Nonsect Radical factions have reinvigorated their activities—for example, by staging “student hunger strikes” in front of the Diet in opposition to the {{ill|Security Legislation|ja|安保関連法案|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Security Legislation|qq=}} and by establishing “alternative spaces” in various locales for activist networking.

== New Left Organizations Derived from Nonsect Radical ==
Among the Nonsect Radical groups, some eventually went on to form permanent New Left factions.
* {{ill|East Asian Anti-Japanese Armed Front|ja|東アジア反日武装戦線|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/East Asian Anti-Japanese Armed Front|qq=}} (Founded in {{ill|1972|ja|1972年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1972|qq=}} (Showa 47))

== References ==
* 『'''{{ill|Monthly Public Safety Forum|ja|月刊治安フォーラム|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Monthly Public Safety Forum|qq=}}'''』, September 2007 Issue
* {{ill|Koichi Toyama|ja|外山恒一|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Koichi Toyama|qq=}} and {{ill|Fumito Nakagawa|ja|中川文人|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fumito Nakagawa|qq=}}, eds., 『Post-Student Movement History: The Hōdaikuro Hel Edition 1985–1994』, Sairyusha, January 2010, ISBN 477911487X
* Comprehensive Magazine for Transformation “Jōkyō” (Spring 2020 Issue) {{ill|Jōkyō Publishing|ja|情況出版|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōkyō Publishing|qq=}}

